<br>
Galain's moment of clarity had befallen him. Now he stood at the river's edge holding on to the balcony, the water flowing freely past below. Candra stood facing him, her picture one of beauty and radiance. The pair had been talking together most of the morning. Their recent time apart had bonded them closer now than they had ever been.<br>
<br>
He moved close wrapping his arms around her waist, pulling her close to him. lost in the warmth of his wife’s embrace Galain's mind felt free of everything. He slowly opened his eyes.<br>
<br>
It was then that he saw something. The warm caress had cleared his thoughts and now he stood looking at the light reflecting off the passing water to the banks of the other side of the stream. He strained to see what it was that he glimpsed through the movement, but the harder he tried to grasp that sense the more distant it became.<br>
<br>
A wash of dread came over Galain, sending the magician's mind reeling. The moment it came it was gone. He stood there with his beloved wife in his arms his mind searching for that elusive thought which so quickly left.<br>
<br>
His heart was pounding in his ears. All he could see was Candra's violet eyes.<br>
<br>
“Galain! Are you alright”. The enchantress' words at first distant becoming clearer as he came crashing back against the present moment.<br>
<br>
Galain stood facing her, The look on her face betraying her worry. With a reassuring smile on his face, he nodded,“I am fine my love.”<br>
<br>
His smiling countenance hid the worry streaming through his mind and the chilling feeling of Dread and fear at what he had glimpsed. Now, he stood silent as he chose his words. From the look on Candra's face he knew the attempt at easing his wife's worries had failed. “She knows me too well,&quot; he thought.<br>
<br>
Galain paused to reorganize his thoughts and started to speak but stopped then he caught Candra’s expression. The woman's unbelievably violet eyes followed something behind him.<br>
<br>
Galain turned to catch a look at what had stolen his love's attention. He followed her gaze to a young Elf who was walking purposely along. The youth's face was slightly turned in a way that brought shadows against his features, defeating Galain's effort to gauge his intentions.<br>
<br>
The flow of time slowed to a crawl as Galain took in the scene. A heavy blanket of silence fell over the world. All his senses were siezed by the actions of the young elf moving ever closer. Galain felt the pounding of the young elf’s feet against the pavement as he walked. <br>
<br>
Young men had a way of carrying themselves. There was typically a hint of uncertainty to their actions. This one lacked such traits. The unsur footing of one so young was gone. The grace of his every step seemed something unnatural. No measure of energy seemed wasted, his every motion spoke of an assurance that belied his age. <br>
<br>
Galain observed the confidence that exuded off the boy's posture, then looked up along the lines of his body in effort to catch the face that seemed purposely hidden away. <br>
<br>
Something cruel and wicked stared back into Galain's face. Something in the magician's mind clicked, warning him that this was no youth - failing to name what &quot;It&quot; was.<br>
<br>
A sudden Dread overwhelmed Galain as he looked into the lifeless eyes of what he had thought was a young Elf. The elusive thought from before was returning. Though to call it a thought was to demean it. This was something more subtle and still more powerful than any mere thought. It was something primal and unsconscious, but stronger than any instinct Galain had known before.<br>
<br>
A voice could be heard, distant and echoing. It's shape was feminine and assertive. The voice of a woman. It was Candra shouting something behind him, but he couldn’t make out what it was. He was too enrapt by the thing that approached him; transfixed by the Dread thing slowly drawing a sword.<br>
<br>
It was the Guards behind skidding to a stop that brought Galain back to his senses. He saw them clawing their way to their feet, distancing themselves from this terror. They had come upon the scene after hearing Candra's shouts, but fear had stopped them in their tracks.<br>
<br>
Looking back to the advancing elf shell, Galain felt panicked. It was almost upon him. He closed his eyes and then his mind off from the thing, freeing himself of its mesmerising effect. The magician focused his thoughts and started to incant.<br>
<br>
Galain's eyes snapped open as the last words trailed from his mouth. He saw the advancing figure stop, its dead eyes staring intently at him. Its face contorted and stretched.<br>
A screaming cry came from its lips as Fire poured from the sky, the heat blistering and tearing at its skin.<br>
<br>
The closeness of the burning form made Galain wince through the heat and the sickening smell of burning flesh. Still, he couldn’t tear his eyes away.<br>
<br>
Dread turned to fear as he stared into the eyes of the monster before him. The world had gone mad, or so Galain hoped. His gut told him it wasn't so, that it was just him. Galain's head shook from side to side and his stomach became queazy. Standing front of him screaming wasn’t a nameless terror, but a simple elf boy. Fear writhed across his face as his skin started to peal and blister. His eyes rolled back into his head as the burning corpse fell to the floor with a sickening thud.<br>
<br>
No one moved, none could speak. The smell of burning flesh assaulted everyone senses. The charred mass lay there, Its hairless head blackened, skin stretched back showing his teeth in a mocking grin.<br>
<br>
