<br>
As nightfall neared Galain found himself resting on a bench not far from where the whole horrible scene had played out before. He sat with his face in his hands as he spoke quietly with General Jyleel. The two elves had been friends for the better part of two centuries; since they were just a pair of boys touring the woods of Kelethin in search of adventure. Their friendship endured over the years, but to a lesser extent as each pursued his own destiny. For the very first time, their paths crossed in a way that could potentially pit one against the other.<br>
<br>
Jyleel was a proud Paladin with a powerful respect for justice, but not the patience that Galain had expected of a man of his station. Jyleel knew the boy that lay dead only a few feet away. He named him for Galain, &quot;I'm a friend to Yadien's family. The lad had hopes of becoming a paladin of my order. I had high hopes for this one, Galain...that he would one day grow enough in power to be worthy of joining the guard and taking up the defense of Felwithe.&quot;<br>
<br>
It was hard to ignore the intense emotions that shaped the general's features. He had taken the news badly, but with reports from the Guards that had witnessed the event he had calmed enough to listen to the full story before speaking. &quot;This was not the boy's way Galain. Yadien is...was...he was a good boy. He would not stoop this way. His family is one of honor! He would have...” The general's grief overwhelmed him. He choked back tears and lowered his head.<br>
<br>
Galain placed his hand on the General's shoulder as a comfort and nodded, &quot;I understand, my friend. The events as reported sustain my opinion that it was not the boy that attacked me. It was something else. Something I cannot explain at this time”.<br>
<br>
Candra sat talking with Seria Woodwind, who frequently held audience with the General. From a short distance away she listened to Galain try and explain what he had felt and seen. She could &quot;feel&quot; the guilt and sense of betrayal that wracked her love's mind for slaying one so young. It was more than she could bear. Seeing that words no longer furthered anything between the Mage and Paladin, she excused herself from Seria's company and rose from her seat. <br>
<br>
She moved towards bench the two elves shared and gently dropped her hand upon Galain's shoulder. Alerted to her presence, Galain looked over his shoulder to find the enchantress' expression dressed by a smile he found immediately comforting. Her voice moved through his ears with a soft touch, like feathers. &quot;Time to go, my love. We should let the General tend to his duties.&quot;<br>
<br>
Galain watched Candra's face with certain curiosity. He sensed meaning in the words she spoke. He could hear something more than just a desire to comfort, but a subtle warning as well. He searched her violet eyes, pleading for a more direct message, but received none. He turned to the Jyleel without meaning to and found the elf completely crest-fallen. The two keeping him company seemed to be in on something that he had clearly overlooked. <br>
<br>
Galain averted his face to not seem so dumbfounded. The action put his gaze on a pair of clerics attending to young Yadien's remains. His mind wandered a bit, speculating on the unfulfilled potential of that life lost. He wondered about the friends and family that would miss his presence in their lives. <br>
<br>
Comprehension dawned suddenly, blinding Galain's mind's eye. He realized now the duty which Candra alluded to earlier. Jyleel would be going now to speak with Yadien's parents. He figured he must have looked distraught as Candra settled beside him to comfort him with a warm hug.<br>
<br>
A silence came over them all. It was so heavy and saturating that it made everything surreal. Finally the General broke that quiet, “Go Galain. Leave it with me. I will speak of this to them. It is not the first time I have done so, and am certain it wont be the last.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bowing to them both Jyleel turned and left, leaving the pair to their grief and the comforts of each others' arms.<br>
