<br>
The dwarven warrior Hardolar stood near the Tiger's Roar musing over the events of the day when a strange event unfolded before him. A strange hum filled the very air around him. A point of space not far from him stirred, the air rippling wildly like waves of heat. He frowned deeply and reached for his sword, muttering, &quot;Magic..&quot;<br>
<br>
Hardolar had been walking the two thin valleys that led to the Tigers Roar. The layout of the area was such that a huge host could be stopped by a very small force and more so now that archery stations had been placed upon the upper most reaches.<br>
<br>
He had been musing over the recent accident that had taken the life of Karthanon. A boulder had slipped from its place, leaving tragedy in its wake. Gilber was killed instantly and Karthanons legs were crushed - leading to his subsequent demise. The very same defenses now built and manned by men and women at arms.<br>
<br>
&quot;Stay your hand Hardolar&quot; came a voice.<br>
<br>
The dwarf relaxed visibly and shot an unfriendly smile at the familiar voice that moved through the event. A moment later that same smile was given to the magician, Galain Whitegloves, who simply appeared in front of him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ye gads it be about time ya arrived back here, Whitegloves! Typical that ya come when all the hard work be done.&quot;<br>
<br>
Smiling, Galain placed his hand on the old Dwarfs shoulder, &quot;Good to see you too, my old friend? Such a wonderful warm greeting.&quot; A light smirk put his mouth in motion. The magician then stepped aside to reveal the rather alluring creature who accompanied him.<br>
<br>
Candra stood there, serene and exotic. With her sun-kissed complexion, dark hair and unbelievably violet eyes, Galain considered his bride easily beautiful and knew in fact that most others agreed. As did she. Some were put off by her confident, cool manner. Galain knew a different side of the human echantress that few were privy to. She was a woman of incredible passion. He'd seen it explode many times, in both temper and joy; and in private moments. Candra's passion was the quality he most admired.<br>
<br>
The enchantress smiled at the awkwardness of the Dwarf as he stammered an apology for his brisk greeting. She graciously bowed when the Dwarf eventually regained enough composure to correct the slight with a warmed smile and a proper salute.<br>
<br>
Galain's missive sent to Hardolar had arrived two weeks before his arrival. It simply read, <br>
<br>
&quot;Possible attack by ReaMorda.<br>
Fortify and prepare for all out defense of the Tigers Roar.&quot;<br>
-Galain<br>
<br>
Much of the defenses had been completed. Now, only the odd workman meandered around on the various tasks still nearing finish.<br>
<br>
Galain inspected them as he walked towards the Tigers Roar. Hardolar pointed out special emplacements of archery stations and their positioning. “Karth started the work before the accident, the two stations upon the ridge there was his idea,” The warrior pointed to the high ridges where the two valleys came together.<br>
<br>
“Any host has ta come through one o' them there passes, or both! They come together here and as they do these two stations will hit that force on both flanks. Be bloody murder to any that tries, it will,”<br>
<br>
The trio continued round to the Tiger's Roar's exterior, Hardolar pointing out various other traps and emplacements forming the outer defenses.<br>
<br>
Upon reaching the inn Galain was met with a sight he wasn’t quite prepared for. The friendly sight of the inn had gone. What was once a picturesque setting of tranquility and beauty now stood as a fortress.<br>
<br>
Archery stations adorned the roof; the path leading up to a wall of sharpened pikes and sentry posts now staggered the main entrance. They weaned their way down the lines of pikes and defenses, fashioned to hinder a straight path to the doors to slow any advancing horde down to a snails pace allowing arrows to be rained down from the emplacements above.<br>
<br>
The going was slow for the three as they wound their way down the path. Candra spoke very little, but quietly communicated her thoughts to Galain with subtle looks and slight gestures. After the long tour, she darted a look at Galain that hinted of weariness. Galain quietly nodded a reply to her.<br>
<br>
“My thanks go to you Hardolar for seeing the work started by Karthanon finished. It is a sad loss for us, his demise. His swords will be missed, especially in these darkening times,”<br>
<br>
The Dwarf puffed visibly, giving one of his infectious smiles. With a crisp salute, he excused himself from his company and turned about, barking out orders with renewed vigor.<br>
<br>
Eventually the day passed, as days are known to do. Galain had spent most of the day in his office, pouring over plans and maps and missives. The Enchantress quietly kept him company while he worked. She lay across the long chair that sat in his private room. Galain had originally requested the seat appointed to the room for private meetings, but Candra had taken to using it. All who came in knew that it was her place. <br>
<br>
The chair was fashioned from the softest hides and dyed the deepest mauve; almost to the point of being black. Its legs were fashioned from the hardest of oaks.It was designed for comfort and Candra often used it to full advantage when wanting her way.<br>
<br>
Few could persuade Galain as his enchantress could and often did. She could lighten the foulest of his moods with just a look. A small ache formed in his chest as considered how close he recently came to losing her love, their very marriage. He was glad now that those rough times were behind them and had endeavored with every passing moment to make sure he never risked it again.<br>
<br>
Indeed, it gave Galain certain comfort to have his wife nearby. Throughout the day he had looked up from his toilings to see her lounged laguorously over &quot;her&quot; chair, comfortable and without any obvious worry.<br>
<br>
His work behind him, Galain looked on still. Candra's soft face glowed for the candle at her side. The odd breeze caused that small, but brilliant flame to flicker - causing shadows to move over her features. It was that contrast Galain loved in her. He knew she hosted hidden depths. He'd only glimpsed before. Maybe one day he would delve into those mysteries, but then again perhaps not. Regardless, his love for the enchantress was complete and unconditional. He was happy just to know she loved him and that was all he needed.<br>
<br>
Galain made his way over to Candra hoping to share the seat. She smiled up at him without speaking and made room to accomodate him. They laid against each other, her head on his chest and an arm draped over his belly. He in turn stroked a hand gently over her dark hair, occasionally catching the silky threads between his fingers. A glass of brandy occupied his other hand. They passed the time talking through the night about the events unfolding; briefly discussing the fortress that now surrounded them.<br>
<br>
Galain sipped at his drink and smiled down along the length of his body at Candra. No more words came from her lips. She'd fallen into a peaceful sleep. He idly wondered about the dreams of an enchantress. &quot;What a wonderland it must be, Candra,&quot; muttered softly as he pulled the hair from her face.<br>
<br>
Even in slumber, her cherry colored and often flavored lips, still held a softly shaped, reassuring smile. It brought little comfort, for he knew that the possible attack by House ReaMorda was just a hint at the Dread that both could feel fast approaching. He clung to his love for warmth and closed his eyes in hopes of joining her in Wonderland.<br>
