<br>
Candra found herself moving swiftly through the night. She was searching for something, though she was not at all sure what that something was. There was a certain urgency to the steps that propelled her onward. Energy drawn from the anxiety that threatened to overwhelm the enchantress fueled her quickening pace.<br>
<br>
She seemed outside of herself, detached from the world she found herself running through. Currently, she was utterly and hopelessly lost. She panned her gaze over the scene laid out before her hoping to land her sights on something that might reveal where she was and why she was there.<br>
<br>
Whatever city this was, Candra could see that it had been great once upon a time. The ruined architecture still boasted some amazing details; grand archways, handsome columns. There was an inherent grace about the structures that had endured in spite of the entropy and decay that was so rampant.<br>
<br>
Candra marveled silently as she pressed forward through the littered avenues. &quot;This is not the effect of time..&quot; she whispered to no one at all. Indeed, there seemed to be no one about at all save the enchantress. Despite the empty streets and lack of life signs anywhere, she had the distinct sense that she was not alone.<br>
<br>
A chill breeze tickled the back of her neck causing her skin to prickle. That sense of someone watching her intensified tenfold. Fear spurred her to action and she turned about to see what had come upon her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Welcome home, Candra.&quot; Yadien greeted the enchantress with a life-mocking smile. His cindered mouth curled back into an impossible grin that caused what remained of his lips to crack and fall away. His burnt and blistered skin filled the gap between the two with a putrid smell that tested the strength of Candra's stomach.<br>
<br>
The enchantress' mind was reeling. She wanted to turn away from the horrible sight of Yadien, but could not as she was so caught up in the dreadful effect of its power.<br>
<br>
&quot;This is not my home.&quot; she heard herself say in reply. Candra couldn't remember speaking, but it was certainly her voice as she knew it in her head.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye, it is milady. Have a look around. See the amazing sights and splendor of the famed city of the High Elves!&quot; The burnt elf gestured with dramatic flair, causing his charred skin to crackle and flake. Candra thought him a little over the top, but couldn't argue with his success. She was very afraid.<br>
<br>
She followed his direction, so mezmerized that she could not stop herself. Ghosts appeared in her vision, faintly shaped things that seemed imposed over the gloom of the ruined city. Candra watched in horror as the ghosts of herself and a young elf sat on the banks of the pond where both shared their first kiss. Her vision shifted suddenly and she could see the ghost of her grandmother standing outside the Keepers of the Art building debating her fellows. Candra's vision blurred for a moment. When it cleared she saw Galain's ghost kneeling before hers as he presented a ring.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now that was a lovely moment,&quot; the corpse said mockingly. He breathed a rancid breath against Candra's skin as he laughed. The enchantress just stood there, frozen and silent as the moment unfolded.<br>
<br>
&quot;Then again, why should you care about this ruined place, my 'Lady of Mysteries'? Felwithe was never your home to begin with, was it.&quot; Yadien's words had the structure of a question, but he made it a flat statement; something to be agreed with. &quot;How could something so common as Freeport's human trash ever hope to find a home here? But then, you've always been the ambitious sort. You've an interesting pedigree, but many pets do, love.&quot;<br>
<br>
The familiar sting of tears reddened Candra's violet eyes. She could feel the tears tumbling down her cheeks despite her best efforts to dam her eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm left to wonder what the Tears of Veeshan would think if they knew about what's hidden in that oh so blue blood of yours.&quot; Yadien came in close, she could feel the heat that radiated off his still smoldering flesh. &quot;Methinks they might just declare a hunt...&quot;<br>
<br>
With that Candra had had enough. She closed her eyes tight and willed herself away from the ruins of Felwithe and the dark thing she knew was not Yadien.<br>
<br>
When finally she opened her eyes, Candra found herself in Galain's slumbering arms. She was trembling despite the warmth that came off her love's body. Desperate for comfort, she moved herself to be even closer against him, waking the magician in the process.<br>
<br>
Galain caught sight of the tears that glittered in her eyes and instictively drew her against him. &quot;What's wrong, love?&quot;<br>
<br>
Candra said nothing in reply, which was fine with Galain. He was there for her as she needed without condition. He would simply hold her until whatever sadness or fear that had gripped her relented and allowed sleep to claim her once again. <br>
<br>
