<br>
The Eastern Plains of Karana is a rough, hilly area on the eastern edge of the Plains of Karana. The area is frequented by many of the rarest and most dangerous creatures in all of Antonica, and is connected to the rest of the world only by two narrow mountain passes and one massive bridge. <br>
<br>
“And to think some intrepid souls make their homes out here amidst these creatures,” Candra mused quietly. She’d hunted the region back in her days as a journeyman among the Champions of the Light. Back then, she had not been ready for the dangers lying in wait and was forced to adapt quickly or face certain death. <br>
<br>
Having survived and surpassed those times by many seasons, she now idly considered the very dangerous and aggressive creatures that roamed the land; many of which were similar to other areas of the Plains of Karana, such hill giants and griffawns; and many more which were unique to the East Karana, such as the gnoll and undead reavers, gorge hounds and war wolves, evil eyes, lion and lioness royalty. She accepted there was a lot of good hunting in the area, but it came at the price of being very dangerous.<br>
<br>
The enchantress stood just a few feet beyond the great bridge of East Karana. A slave to fashion, Candra was dressed for traveling. She left behind her ornately designed robe for a simpler look; a dark leather tunic and matching leggings, with boots gloves and a cloak that caught the wind blowing about her. Choosing the proper attire was one of the lessons learned so many years ago. <br>
<br>
With care, Candra moved away from the bridge and made her way to the riverbank. A cool breeze gusted from the north. It surged over her face and played brusquely through her raven hair. Powerful enchantments cast on her person took the chill out of the wind. Despite its rough play Candra considered the wind a small pleasure. Karana’s firm caress gave her a measure of comfort as she moved towards a meeting that would surely test her resolve to master the mystery of the wicked thing that had recently touched her mind. <br>
<br>
In hope of finding some shred of a clue about that dark power, Candra tasked two lesser enchantresses sworn the Champions’ to join her in High Castle’s vast library. The Erudite, Yazmine and High Elf, Sandianya willingly lent their able minds to the cause. Their coven spent days toiling over the many tomes, scrolls and maps that lined its expansive walls. For all the time invested there was little information to be found.<br>
<br>
It was Yazmine who was able to connect a fragile thread of folktales to the dark power that haunted Candra’s dreams. It was Sandianya who connected those tales to an ancient order of explorers and adventurers known as the Immaculate Order of Dragons. According to those tales, the “Dragons” had warred with an entity bent on the ruin of all creation. It had the power to invade minds and possess bodies, thus making it a difficult force to confront. However, as the tales explained it, the Dragons’ dedication eventually led to the destruction of that dark power.<br>
<br>
In Candra’s mind there was no doubt that all their research was pointing in the right direction. Whatever the Dragons’ had done to destroy the force had not been sufficient, if the stories were at all accurate. There was only one way to know for sure.<br>
<br>
Candra left her two aids to their rest and fled High Castle in search of more answers. The threads they had gathered weren’t so fragile in the end. In fact, the eldest of the enchanters left their research with a solid lead that could very well put a name to the force at large.<br>
<br>
So, now she found herself in East Karana seeking out the one man who could give the missing pieces to the puzzle she sought to solve. It was no great feat for her to learn his whereabouts. Candra simply asked her mirror to show him to her. She then turned to her guildmate, the druidess Nivya, for transport. It all happened so fast that Candra hadn’t actually formed a plan for her approach. She simply moved towards his general direction, hoping the way would become clear with each step.<br>
<br>
Candra’s violet gaze lighted on a small boat afloat towards the center of the waterway. She was suddenly uneasy and nervous, but still determined to meet with him. She closed her eyes for a moment and sucked in a breath, then released it slowly to steady her nerves. She walked over to the water’s edge and incanted in a gentle voice. Rings of magic sprung from her gesturing hands, bathing the enchantress in a brief emerald aura that lifted her into the air. Feeling she was as prepared as she could be, Candra floated over the gently flowing water towards the boat.<br>
<br>
The sounds of the flowing river masked her already quiet arrival. An fisherman sat in the boat, a fishing rod in his hands and a rather fine looking pipe caught between his lips. Candra stood at his back, searching for the words to greet him.<br>
<br>
“It’s a bit rude to just stand there staring, don’t you think?” His spoke in a rich baritone that resonated throughout Candra’s being. <br>
<br>
“I suppose it is,” she replied in a voice that was strangely shy. <br>
<br>
The fisherman stood to his feet without even threatening to upset his small craft. Candra considered the feat uncanny and it showed in her eyes. He regarded her with a smile that could melt glaciers, “It’s been some time, my dear. How are you, Candra?”<br>
<br>
The sound of that voice uttering her name sent a chill through the enchantress, but she managed to resist its power, much like she had his smile. Candra’s cool could outdo a glacier on her best day. “I’m fine. How are you, father?”<br>
