<br>
Tytalus Verbana appeared much the same as Candra remembered him; long haired, mustached, and possessed of innate charm. His swarthy complexion was highlighted by prominent cheekbones and a pair of green eyes that captivated all who met his gaze. His strong, aristocratic nose suggested his noble ancestry. <br>
<br>
Candra quietly marveled at his timeless good-looks. Indeed, the man looked remarkably ageless for a human. Then again, no one knew better than an enchantress that looks could be deceiving. She couldn’t help but pry a little, “You’re looking remarkably well, father.”<br>
<br>
“Shall I say ‘Thank you’ and pretend your interest is a compliment?”<br>
<br>
A light smirk played over Candra’s lips. Candra liked a challenge and there was no one more challenging than her father. He had always been little larger than life when she was a young girl. His presence filled any room he entered. <br>
<br>
As she journeyed to this meeting, Candra had thought that effect would be diminished by his greater years and the harsh times he’d endured. The looking glass related a vague figure, somewhat obscured, she believed, by magic meant to foul attempts to scry his whereabouts. She filled in the blanks herself and believed the wizard to be old, tired and broken, a fallen champion whose power was but a whisper of the bellow it used to be. Well, you know what they say about when one “assumes”, she thought.<br>
<br>
Candra showed the man a slight grin as she replied to his obviously rhetorical question, “You’ll do as you please. You always have.”<br>
<br>
“Where are my manners?” Tytatlus extended his hand to the levitating enchantress. His mustache lent the grin bending his lips a feral charm. “Come aboard, won’t you? I’m afraid the accommodations here may not be suiting to a lady of your refined tastes. My, err...yacht is out for repairs.” He shot her a wink and showed his white teeth.<br>
<br>
Candra accepted the invitation and took the man’s hand. Contrary to popular belief, she had spent many a day on a similar boat enjoying the very same sport. She found the relative peace of fishing a wonderful exercise of patience and meditation. Her movements proved that fact as she easily situated herself to settle into the boats meager comforts.<br>
<br>
If Tytalus noticed her confidence, he didn’t let it show. “So what brings you about after so many years, my dear? I would like to think the call is purely social, but I know you better than that.”<br>
<br>
Candra didn’t waste any time feigning hurt feelings or shock in the face of brutal honesty. She saw no reason for the soft and gentle approach, she wasn’t feeling much in the mood to play around anyway, “I need your help to unravel a mystery. One that I feel will become a threat to the Realm if allowed to go on unchecked.”<br>
<br>
Intrigued, Tytalus leaned forward towards her. “Please continue.”<br>
<br>
Candra did her best to relay the story of the young paladin, Yadien and then the dreams, or rather nightmares, which haunted her sleep. She told him of the auguries she’d cast and of the sense of dread that had made its home in her heart.<br>
<br>
Tytalus listened eagerly to all she had to say, enrapt by the telling. Candra could only guess at the thoughts that ran through his mind. She dared not steal them. It would be considered rude if she was caught in the act, then too her father’s sanity was rumored to be a fragile thing and she, as a rule, shied away from prying into the minds of the mad. <br>
<br>
The enchantress searched through the wild look in the wizard’s wondrous green eyes. They were full of questions that were already tripping over his tongue to be asked.<br>
<br>
Tytalus stammered, “Tell me about the elf Yadien. Did the clerics make any effort to recall his soul to his body?”<br>
<br>
Candra held on to his gaze. “Yes, but they could not call it back. Something about...”<br>
<br>
A look of dread washed over Tytalus’ face. He turned slightly, looking away. Candra couldn’t determine if he did for distraction or to hide the growing fear she read in his expression. “It swallows souls, Candra. Leaving nothing but the shell behind.”<br>
<br>
He looked her up and down as if sizing her up. “These nightmares you speak of....I’m curious. Did you touch Its mind, Candra?”<br>
<br>
It was a detail she’s not told anyone. His intense look compelled her to answer him with honesty. “Yes.”<br>
<br>
“And what did you see there?”<br>
<br>
She was trembling and could not stop herself from doing so as she called that memory to present thought. “I saw a creature comprised of darkness and death. It thrived for the power of the souls it had consumed and was bent on a singular mission.”<br>
<br>
“What mission, Candra? Tell me! I must know!”<br>
<br>
“It...It intends to murder the world.” For her brief contact with the dark force that had possessed Yadien, Candra had caught a glimpse at something powerful and unique. A force of destruction the likes of which she’d never thought possible. It had the presence of a god, but lacked the power. She considered Its potential and ambition and couldn’t help but wonder -“What is 'It', father?”<br>
<br>
“I cannot say.”<br>
<br>
“Cannot or will not?” she demanded<br>
<br>
Tytalus turned on his daughter with wild, wide eyes, his voice charged with restrained power. “CANNOT!” The boat swayed violently, rocked by the churning waters that floated it.<br>
<br>
Candra felt dizzy, taken aback by the magic that emanated from the wizard. She found herself suffocating in the presence of such a phenomenon. She struggled against it, gripping the boat’s rim to steady herself. She looked back at her father with a pleading look.<br>
<br>
Tytalus caught her look and took control of his self. An apology shaped his expression as he reigned in the magic that had, for a moment, gotten away from him.<br>
<br>
Candra said nothing. She simply looked at the man across from her. Tytalus sat there, hugging himself. He seemed so vulnerable, but the display of power he’d shown warned Candra towards caution. A part of her longed to go to Tytalus and comfort him, but she was altogether too afraid; of his power, of losing time.<br>
<br>
Her lips parted to loose a voice so soft it fell over her father’s senses like the touch of feathers. A gentle breeze washed over the man, clearing his mind, sharpening his focus. “Please father, help me.”<br>
<br>
Tytalus seemed transformed as he looked back at Candra. There was a clear look in his eyes and his voice carried the same trait. ”It was centuries ago, m’dear, during a time that has come to be known as the Lost Age. The orcs had not yet settled into Greater Faydark and the outpost Firiona Vie was not even conceived in thought.<br>
<br>
&quot;The progenitors of the Immaculate Order of Dragons had not yet finished constructing their keep when a powerful threat...a danger unlike any they had known came upon the Realm and made fast plans to murder it. The Order gathered its allies and journeyed en masse in search of a beast that could leap from form to form. After countless lives had been lost It was still at large; pursuing an agenda that confounded all who ran after It. It was an event that the guild’s historians dubbed ‘The Great Contagion” for It swept over the land like a plague. In the end the Order and its allies prevailed against its foe, but they lacked a means to destroy its life. It is said that a great circle of powerful spell casters from each of the guilds gathered to cast a work of will that bound the beast in the empty void of space and time, thus bringing that awful chapter of history to a close.”<br>
<br>
Candra seemed confused, “How is it that I’ve never heard this before?”<br>
<br>
“There is a reason why they call it the Lost Age, Candra.”<br>
<br>
She nodded and to her credit didn’t blush for the embarrassment she felt. “Tell me more.”<br>
<br>
“You’ve heard all that I remember.”<br>
<br>
“It’s not enough, father. I need to know it’s name, its purpose and how, if all you’ve said is true, it escaped its prison.”<br>
<br>
Tytalus grinned. It was obvious the wizard was impressed by his daughter’s drive. He nodded. “There is one who can provide the information you seek.”<br>
<br>
Candra’s violet eyes blazed with curiosity. “Tell me!”<br>
<br>
Tytalus’ green eyes leveled to that determined gaze as he submitted to his daughter’s demand. He uttered only one word in reply. “Wuoshi.”<br>
