<br>
A rush of warm air breathed over Candra’s body as she appeared in Wakening Land. It was a welcome sensation after leaving the harsh cold of the Great Divide. She slowly stepped away from the portal, moving towards the center of the druid circle. The druid Halai had arrived moments before her and stood patiently, waiting.<br>
<br>
Candra met up with the elf, offering him a smile as warm as their environs. “Thank you, Halai. You’ve been so helpful, considering...”<br>
<br>
“Considering that what you intend to do is madness!” There was no apology to follow for his snapping remark. From the moment the enchantress explained her reasons for seeking him out, Halai had done his best to talk her out it.<br>
<br>
Decided in her course of action, Candra would not be swayed to change. She ignored his warning. The anxiety that gripped her stomach was already great and no good could come from further exposure to discouraging words.<br>
<br>
She took a moment to shrug off the furs that wrapped her shapely figure to reveal a form flattering tunic and matching leggings. With Coldain skin boots and gloves, she was a study of warm tones, browns and golds. Her dark hair was gathered into a thick braid that fell just shy of the center of her back.<br>
<br>
Her violet gaze swept over the area as she considered The Wakening Land. It was a large forested valley on an otherwise frozen continent. The goddess Tunare had a very palpable presence, and was likely the reason that the area was so full of life. Candra moved away from the ring’s center, stepping towards the egress.<br>
<br>
Halai followed after her, his mouth still moving. As he had yet to say anything that would encourage her, Candra was still ignoring him. She suddenly felt his gentle grip on her bicep, tugging her towards him. She turned to face her guildsman with a curious look drawn over her features.<br>
<br>
“I have faith in you, M’Lady.” His words rang with a sincerity that was echoed by his expression. His eyes held such concern. “Do not think for one moment that I do not. That which you seek is a powerful force and I only mean to urge you towards caution. It is madness for you to go alone.”<br>
<br>
“Trust in that faith, my friend. I do what must be done. This is the only way.”<br>
<br>
The druid seemed unconvinced, but was all talked out. He gave Candra a slow nod and took a step back as assent. “I shall wait for you here then, Regentia. May the Great Mother see you through this and return you safely to me soon.”<br>
<br>
She shared a reassuring smile with Halai, then turned away to leave the circle.<br>
<br>
Away from the Dragon Portal, Candra expected to be greeted with dramatic silence. She imagined an ominous, deep quiet to guide her path. The reality was that the moment she crossed over the circle’s threshold her senses were assaulted by signs of a great battle nearby. <br>
<br>
The smells of blood and magic rode the warm wind. Clashing weapons and cries of anguish rang in her ears. Her mind was reeling from fear and surprise. She turned about, spinning and searching for the source of such bedlam.<br>
<br>
Her eyes landed on a sight that was as amazing as it was terrible. Either, a group of adventurers had made the mistake of entering The Wakening Land unaware of the great dragon that made its home there, or they had come to seek it out with the intention of slaying the great beast for the fame and wealth that such a kill would bring them.<br>
<br>
Candra’s heart sank as she glanced over the mangled bodies that littered the ground; streams of crimson connecting them. She turned to those still standing and ached for the imminent loss of life. There were three of them. Candra studied each and guessed them to be a human cleric, and a Feir’Dal druid and ranger. There was nothing she could do to help them as she was unwilling to compromise her standing with the flight of dragons that made up the sect known as the Claws of Veeshan. Any attempt to help these poor souls would certainly earn the dragon’s enmity and deliver her into Death’s embrace.<br>
<br>
A splatter of blood and bits of gore had ruined the golden armor of the group’s remaining cleric; most of it not his own. The human struggled with a prayer for healing, but was cut short by a talon through his breast. The ranger fell soon after, burned to cinders as she tried to save her human companion. The druid was quick to think and took advantage of the moment to cast a spell that would take him away from the carnage. The very air about him rippled as he opened a rift in space-time, but alas, his gate proved unstable. His magic faltered and a powerful sweep of the dragon’s claws put an end to any notion of a second attempt.<br>
<br>
The dragon raised its long neck and roared so fiercely that the world shook. Candra fell to her knees, trembling for reasons besides the shaking ground beneath her feet. She struggled to compose herself, making a great effort to stand. When she had accomplished that feat, the enchantress looked up to find the dragon’s blazing serpentine gaze upon her.<br>
<br>
In that moment of incredible awe, the dragon slowly approaching - all rational thought fled her screaming mind. <br>
